<span id="freeTextContainer1494698259738260181">A novel about a hostage crisis that goes wrong -- with very sexy results, <i>Bel Canto</i> might have been a better read if at some point Patchett did anything to acknowledge the plot&apos;s ridiculousness. Instead, she treats the readers to vague social commentary about South America, multiple nobel savage tropes, and a crisis situation where people do have sex, but only after first taking the time to fall in love. It&apos;s also somewhat about opera, so allow me the metaphor that <i>Bel Canto</i> hits all the obvious</span>
  <span id="freeText1494698259738260181" style="display:none">A novel about a hostage crisis that goes wrong -- with very sexy results, <i>Bel Canto</i> might have been a better read if at some point Patchett did anything to acknowledge the plot's ridiculousness. Instead, she treats the readers to vague social commentary about South America, multiple nobel savage tropes, and a crisis situation where people do have sex, but only after first taking the time to fall in love. It's also somewhat about opera, so allow me the metaphor that <i>Bel Canto</i> hits all the obvious notes with competence but without ever risking enough to engage the audience.<br /><br />Not to be a pure hater, I did love the hell out of the cover art.</span>
